data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. **No migration is needed** for Thread.Abort concerns.

That said, for modern .NET, consider replacing raw threads with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll` for cleaner, more efficient parallelism:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in thread pool management and cancellation support via `CancellationToken`.
